english:
  title: Epitaph for Lady Heo, Consort of Minister Kim Mun-young
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: "Lady Heo bore the surname of the Heo clan, second daughter of Vice-Minister Heo Gong, whose courtesy name was Heo Gong and title was Mungyeong-gong. Her grandfather served as Vice Director of the Chancellery, known as Heo Su, and her great-grandfather held the rank of Court Official for Envoys, known as Heo Gyeong. Her mother was Lady Yun, daughter of Jeongdang Scholar and Civil Servant Mun-pyeong-gong, whose courtesy name was Heo Geuk-min.\n\nFrom birth, Lady Heo was diligent and sincere, earning the deep affection of her father, Mungyeong-gong. When her mother was laid to rest on the day of Eul-chuk, someone petitioned to recalculate the auspicious date based on Lady Heo's birth year. But Mungyeong-gong declared, \"Our daughter shall surely enjoy great fortune—there is no reason to worry.\" \n\nWhen she came of age, her father secured an excellent match: she became the consort of Minister Kim Un, whose title was Mun-young and whose seat was at Sangnak. Both the Kim and Heo families were great houses of considerable wealth, yet Lady Heo maintained propriety and restraint in all things, and none among the people harbored ill words against her. Though Minister Kim in his later years took pleasure in song and the company of entertainers, Lady Heo never showed a trace of jealousy.\n\nTwelve years after her husband's passing, in the seventh month of Jimun year during the At-sun era, on the day of Sinmyo, she departed this life from illness. She bore four sons and three daughters. Her eldest son, Yeong-don, rose to rank of Great Sacrificial Official and Chief of the Bureau of Laws. Her second son, Yeong-hui, became Commander of the Flourishing Guard. Her third son entered monastic life as a Buddhist elder. Her fourth son, Yeong-hu, attained the rank of Grand Counselor and Minister of Resources. Her eldest daughter married Lord Jeong Chaek of Cheongha and preceded her mother in death. Her second daughter married Lord Baek Yi-jeong of Sangdang. Her youngest daughter married the Mongol official Bili Gabulhua, who served as Counselor-in-Chief of the Jiangzhe Province.\n\nThus the epitaph reads:\n\nGentle and upright,\nShe embodied the virtues of a consort.\nGenerrous and gracious,\nHer way was the noble path of mothers.\n\nGlorious Mungyeong-gong\nWho discerned with perfect clarity—\nHow much more shall his children\nReap the benefits of such wisdom.\n\nA worthy companion to the gentleman,\nVirtuous and blessed with long life,\nThis inscription upon the burial mound\nShall speak through endless ages to come."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Minister Kim Un held the title of Sangnakkun (Marquis of Sangnak) and was known as Mun-young-gongja.
  - key: ''
    value: The at-sun year (至順 임신년) refers to 1332 CE during the Yuan Dynasty period.
  - key: ''
    value: The Buddhist monastic elder was named Sasun of the Jeun Order.
